    <h1>Cuts</h1>
    <h3>Small Cuts</h3>
    <p> Small cuts or abrasions are usally not a big emergence if they are treated correctly. If they are not treated properly they can become infected or not heal properly.</p>
    <h4> How to treat a small cut</h4>
    <ol>
      <li> Clean with water</li>
      <li> Dry with cloth</li>
      <li> Apply tripple antibiotic ointment</li>
      <li> Wrap with steral bandage</li>
    </ol>
    <h3>Large Cuts</h3>
    <p> Large cuts can be more severe than small ones. Depending on where they are located on the body, they can be life theatening. If there is significent loss of blood or if all the layer of skin are exposed seek medical attention</p>
    <h4> How to treat a large cut</h4>
    <ol>
      <li> Assess where the cut is on the body</li>
      <li>Clense with water</li>
      <li> Apply triple antibiotic ointment</li>
      <li> Wrap with steril cloth</li>
    </ol>
    <p> If the cut is on a artery then</p>
    <ul> 
      <li>Apply a turnicet</li>
      <li> Keep constent presure on the wound</li>
      <li> Call 911 or your local emergency number</li>
    </ul>
